06592nam a22007575i 9780822381808DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19931993ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223818087 a10.1515/97808223818082doi  a(DE-B1597)553504  a(OCoLC)841913169  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aDS845b.M56 1993 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a952.04922200aJapan in the World /cMasao Miyoshi, Harry Harootunian. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1993] 4cÂ©1993  a1 online resource (371 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tJapan in the World -- tThe World -- tJapan's Industrial Revolution in Historical Perspective -- tThe Prussia of the East? -- tRacism and the State: The Coming Crisis of U.S.-Japanese Relations -- t"Past Experience, If Not Forgotten, Is a Guide to the Future"; or, What Is in a Text? The Politics of History in Chinese-Japanese Relations -- tArchaeology, Descent, Emergence: Japan in British/American Hegemony, 1900-1950 -- tSociety -- tConstructing a New Cultural History of Prewar Japan -- tThe Spirit of Productivity: Workplace Discourse on Culture and Economics in Japan -- tCulture -- tThe Novelist in Today's World: A Conversation -- tSoseki and Western Modernism -- tAmerica's Japan / Japan's Japan -- tIn a Labyrinth of Western Desire: Kuki Shuzo and the Discovery of Japanese Being -- tReturn to the West / Return to the East: Watsuji Tetsuro's Anthropology and Discussions of Authenticity -- tThe Invention of English Literature in Japan -- tThe Discursive Space of Modern Japan -- tTheory's Imaginal Other: American Encounters with South Korea and Japan -- tThe Difficulty of Being Radical: The Discipline of Film Studies and the Postcolonial World Order -- tIndex -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the end of World War II, Japan has determinately remained outside the current of world events and uninvolved in the processes determining global history and politics. In Japan and the World, distinguished scholars, novelists, and intellectuals articulate how Japan-despite unprecedented economic prowess in securing dominance in the world's market-is caught in a complex dependency with the United States. Drawing on critical and postmodernist theory, this timely volume situates this dependency in a broader historical context and assesses Japan's current dealings in international politics, society, and culture.Among the many topics covered are: racism in U.S.-Japanese relations; productivity and workplace discourse; Western cultural hegemony; the constructing of a Japanese cultural history; and the place of the novelist in today's world. Originally published as a special issue of boundary 2 (Fall 1991), this edition includes four new essays on Japanese industrial revolution; the place of English studies in Japan; how American cultural, historical, and political discourse represented Japan and in turn how America's version of Japan became Japan's version of itself; and an "archaeology" of hegemonic relationships between Japan and America and Britain in the first half of the twentieth century.Contributors. Eqbal Ahmad, Perry Anderson, Bruce Cumings, Arif Dirlik, H.D. Harootunian, Kazuo Ishuro, Fredric Jameson, Kojin Karatani, Oe Kenzaburo, Masao Miyoshi, Tetsuo Najita, Leslie Pincus, Naoki Sakai, Miriam Silverberg, Christena Turner, Rob Wilson, Mitsuhiro Yoshimoto  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Perry1 aDirlik, Arif, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCumings, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTurner, Christena, econtributor.4ctb4https